You do not need a `DateTimeFormatter`
--

`java.time` API is based on [ISO 8601](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/ISO_8601) and therefore you do not need a `DateTimeFormatter` to parse a date-time string which is already in ISO 8601 format (e.g. your date-time string, `2022-12-26T14:52:02+08:00`).

**Demo**:

    import java.time.OffsetDateTime;
    
    class Main {
        public static void main(String args[]) {
            String strDateTime = &quot;2022-12-26T14:52:02+08:00&quot;;
            OffsetDateTime odt = OffsetDateTime.parse(strDateTime);
            System.out.println(odt);
        }
    }

**Output**:

    2022-12-26T14:52:02+08:00

Learn more about the modern Date-Time API from **[Trail: Date Time](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/datetime/index.html)**.

